{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"4a7e7f58-840c-46aa-9dbe-3e7c3037ac86","content":"The standard approach is to **wrap file system calls behind an interface** and inject it:\n\n```csharp\npublic interface IFileSystem\n{\n    string ReadAllText(string path);\n    void WriteAllText(string path, string contents);\n    bool DirectoryExists(string path);\n}\n```\n\nThen implement it with the real calls:\n\n```csharp\npublic class FileSystem : IFileSystem\n{\n    public string ReadAllText(string path) => File.ReadAllText(path);\n    public void WriteAllText(string path, string contents) => File.WriteAllText(path, contents);\n    public bool DirectoryExists(string path) => Directory.Exists(path);\n}\n```\n\n**In production**, inject `FileSystem`. **In tests**, mock `IFileSystem` (e.g., via Moq or a hand-written fake) to return controlled data without touching disk.\n\nAlternatively, the **`System.IO.Abstractions`** NuGet package provides a ready-made `IFileSystem` interface covering the full `System.IO` surface, plus a `MockFileSystem` for testing — saves you from maintaining your own wrapper.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"28571b33-0d93-4b04-a2ab-519ceef76def","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about making file system operations testable in a .NET/C# project. This is a design/architecture question about testability, not a code change request. Let me provide a concise answer.","outputTokens":328,"requestId":"981E:2EAF75:115BEBE:15C92E4:69FFE5C4"},"id":"0705943f-6ad9-4d44-91e2-920ad8396503","timestamp":"2026-05-10T01:56:27.740Z","parentId":"3bca7c0d-115b-488c-add1-fb07c3e7306b"}
